IT Budget




Headquartered in Newbury, Micro Focus provides IT services, including software and consultancy products, to its clientele. The company operates in nine countries on four different continents.

In late 2016, the company announced that it is planning a merger with the Hewlett… MoreHeadquartered in Newbury, Micro Focus provides IT services, including software and consultancy products, to its clientele. The company operates in nine countries on four different continents.

In late 2016, the company announced that it is planning a merger with the Hewlett Packard Enterprise Software Division.  Micro Focus acquired Novell in 2015.

Procurement Process:
IT and technology sourcing is managed by the procurement department.
2013 and previously: Led from company headquarters in Newbury, the IT department at Micro Focus is in large part heavily focused on developing applications for the company's customers. The company generally uses its own products whenever possible.

While a Director of… More2013 and previously: Led from company headquarters in Newbury, the IT department at Micro Focus is in large part heavily focused on developing applications for the company's customers. The company generally uses its own products whenever possible.

While a Director of IT oversees all IT operations, a CTO oversees all customer-facing applications development as well as related internal IT tasks. A Chief Architect also handles client-side applications architecture.

Internally, the company has divisions including Applications Development, Solutions Delivery, Support Services, and IT Technology Services. Applications Development largely handles the development of internal business applications that the company purchases from others, while Solutions Delivery focuses on IT project management. Support Services provides IT help desk services, while IT Technology Services handles all internal IT infrastructure tasks, including database administration, data center management, server management, and network operations. Each division provides for its own IT security needs rather than having the company establish an entirely separate division.





